aa(lp43
VHere's an example.
p44
aVFour years ago, I was at the beach with my son,
p45
aVand he was learning how to swim
p46
aVin this relatively soft surf of the Delaware beaches.
p47
aVBut I turned away for a moment, and he got caught into a riptide
p48
aVand started to be pulled out towards the jetty.
p49
aVI can stand here right now and see,
p50
aVas I go tearing into the water after him,
p51
aVthe moments slowing down and freezing into this arrangement.
p52
aVI can see the rocks are over here.
p53
aVThere's a wave about to crash onto him.
p54
aVI can see his hands reaching out,
p55
aVand I can see his face in terror,
p56
aVlooking at me, saying, "Help me, Dad."
p57
aVI got him. The wave broke over us.
p58
aVWe got back on shore; he was fine.
p59
aVWe were a little bit rattled.
p60
aVBut this flashbulb memory, as it's called,
p61
aVis when all the elements came together to define
p62
aVnot just the event, but my emotional connection to it.
p63
aVAnd this is what a photograph taps into
p64
aVwhen it makes its own powerful connection to a viewer.
