aa(lp193
VSometimes, though, the only way to tell a story is with a sweeping picture.
p194
aVWe teamed up underwater photographer Brian Skerry
p195
aVand photojournalist Randy Olson
p196
aVto document the depletion of the world's fisheries.
p197
aVWe weren't the only ones to tackle this subject,
p198
aVbut the photographs that Brian and Randy created
p199
aVare among the best to capture both the human
p200
aVand natural devastation of overfishing.
p201
aVHere, in a photo by Brian,
p202
aVa seemingly crucified shark is caught up
p203
aVin a gill net off of Baja.
p204
aVI've seen sort of OK pictures of bycatch,
p205
aVthe animals accidentally scooped up
p206
aVwhile fishing for a specific species.
p207
aVBut here, Brian captured a unique view
p208
aVby positioning himself underneath the boat
p209
aVwhen they threw the waste overboard.
p210
aVAnd Brian then went on to even greater risk
p211
aVto get this never-before-made photograph
p212
aVof a trawl net scraping the ocean bottom.
p213
aa(lp214
VBack on land, Randy Olson photographed
p215
aVa makeshift fish market in Africa,
p216
aVwhere the remains of filleted fish were sold to the locals,
p217
aVthe main parts having already been sent to Europe.
p218
aVAnd here in China, Randy shot a jellyfish market.
p219
aVAs prime food sources are depleted,
p220
aVthe harvest goes deeper into the oceans
p221
aVand brings in more such sources of protein.
p222
aVThis is called fishing down the food chain.
p223
aa(lp224
VBut there are also glimmers of hope,
p225
aVand I think anytime we're doing a big, big story on this,
p226
aVwe don't really want to go
p227
aVand just look at all the problems.
p228
aVWe also want to look for solutions.
p229
aVBrian photographed a marine sanctuary in New Zealand,
p230
aVwhere commercial fishing had been banned \u2014
p231
aVthe result being that the overfished species have been restored,
p232
aVand with them a possible solution for sustainable fisheries.
