aa(lp234
VPhotography can also compel us to confront
p235
aVissues that are potentially distressing and controversial.
p236
aVJames Nachtwey, who was honored at last year's TED,
p237
aVtook a look at the sweep of the medical system
p238
aVthat is utilized to handle the American wounded coming out of Iraq.
p239
aVIt is like a tube where a wounded soldier enters on one end
p240
aVand exits back home, on the other.
p241
aVJim started in the battlefield.
p242
aVHere, a medical technician tends to a wounded soldier
p243
aVon the helicopter ride back to the field hospital.
p244
aVHere is in the field hospital.
p245
aVThe soldier on the right has the name of his daughter
p246
aVtattooed across his chest, as a reminder of home.
p247
aVFrom here, the more severely wounded are transported
p248
aVback to Germany, where they meet up with their families
p249
aVfor the first time.
p250
aVAnd then back to the States to recuperate at veterans' hospitals,
p251
aVsuch as here in Walter Reed.
p252
aVAnd finally, often fitted with high-tech prosthesis,
p253
aVthey exit the medical system and attempt
p254
aVto regain their pre-war lives.
p255
aVJim took what could have been a straight-up medical science story
p256
aVand gave it a human dimension that touched our readers deeply.
