aa(lp258
VNow, these stories are great examples
p259
aVof how photography can be used
p260
aVto address some of our most important topics.
p261
aVBut there are also times when photographers
p262
aVsimply encounter things that are, when it comes down to it,
p263
aVjust plain fun.
p264
aVPhotographer Paul Nicklin traveled to Antarctica
p265
aVto shoot a story on leopard seals.
p266
aVThey have been rarely photographed, partly because they are considered
p267
aVone of the most dangerous predators in the ocean.
p268
aVIn fact, a year earlier, a researcher had been
p269
aVgrabbed by one and pulled down to depth and killed.
p270
aVSo you can imagine Paul was maybe a little bit hesitant
p271
aVabout getting into the water.
p272
aVNow, what leopard seals do mostly is, they eat penguins.
p273
aVYou know of "The March of the Penguins."
p274
aVThis is sort of the munch of the penguins.
p275
aV(Laughter)
p276
aVHere a penguin goes up to the edge and looks out
p277
aVto see if the coast is clear.
p278
aVAnd then everybody kind of runs out and goes out.
p279
aa(lp280
VBut then Paul got in the water.
p281
aVAnd he said he was never really afraid of this.
p282
aVWell, this one female came up to him.
p283
aVShe's probably \u2014 it's a shame you can't see it in the photograph,
p284
aVbut she's 12 feet long.
p285
aVSo, she is pretty significant in size.
p286
aVAnd Paul said he was never really afraid,
p287
aVbecause she was more curious about him than threatened.
p288
aVThis mouthing behavior, on the right,
p289
aVwas really her way of saying to him, "Hey, look how big I am!"
p290
aVOr you know, "My, what big teeth you have."
p291
aV(Laughter)
p292
aVThen Paul thinks that she simply took pity on him.
p293
aVTo her, here was this big, goofy creature in the water
p294
aVthat for some reason didn't seem to be interested
p295
aVin chasing penguins.
p296
aVSo what she did was she started to bring penguins to him,
p297
aValive, and put them in front of him.
p298
aVShe dropped them off, and then they would swim away.
p299
aVShe'd kind of look at him, like "What are you doing?"
p300
aVGo back and get them, and then bring them back
p301
aVand drop them in front of him.
p302
aVAnd she did this over the course of a couple of days,
p303
aVuntil the point where she got so frustrated with him
p304
aVthat she started putting them directly on top of his head.
p305
aV(Laughter)
p306
aVWhich just resulted in a fantastic photograph.
p307
aV(Laughter)
p308
aVEventually, though, Paul thinks that she just figured
p309
aVthat he was never going to survive.
p310
aVThis is her just puffing out, you know,
p311
aVsnorting out in disgust.
p312
aV(Laughter)
p313
aVAnd lost interest with him, and went back to what she does best.
p314
aa(lp315
VPaul set out to photograph a relatively
p316
aVmysterious and unknown creature,
p317
aVand came back with not just a collection of photographs,
p318
aVbut an amazing experience and a great story.
p319
aVIt is these kinds of stories,
p320
aVones that go beyond the immediate or just the superficial
p321
aVthat demonstrate the power of photojournalism.
p322
aVI believe that photography can make a real connection to people,
p323
aVand can be employed as a positive agent
p324
aVfor understanding the challenges and opportunities
p325
aVfacing our world today.
